This Week in History
1686-1704

Major Events
>Great Turkish War
>Anti-French Wars
>Russian Expansion Eastward
>The Great Northern War

The Great Turkish War (1683-1699)

Last week we covered the Siege of Vienna and the fall of Buda, with the Turks being forced to abandon everything on the North Bank of the Danube and Russia had just sent 140,000 men to crush Crimea.

1687 sees Venice and Russia join the Holy League in writing, Venice seizes most of the Peloponnese Islands by 1688 and begins its invasion of Morea, the southernmost peninsula of Greece. Their contributions are mainly grinding down the Turkish Fleet.
In 1688, the German-Hapsburg forces cross the Danube and take Belgrade, where supported by the Local Serbians drive the Turks from much of Serbia. 1690 saw the Turks abandon their Crimean vassal to the Russians, who overran most of the region, and dealing a heavy blow to the Turks by destroying some 4000 Janissaries and taking the City of Azov. The withdrawal from the East allowed the Turks to relaunch offensives in the Balkans, taking back Nis, and many other Hapsburg held towns in Serbia and Montenegro as the War of the League of Augsburg drew some 100,000 German forces to the newly opened Western Front. The war seemed to be turning against the Holy League until Eugene of Savoy was given control over the army in 1696, where he would issue the Turks a defeat in the final major battle of the War at Zenta where he would lose only 2000 men and kill over 30,000 Turks. I would go over this more but I don't want to make it a 5 post thing. The Turks would lose Hungary, Dalmatia, Azov, a portion of Ukraine, and the war so greatly ravaged the Turkish economic core of the Balkans it sent them into decline.

Here's a mapping video over the entire conflict
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VHhJj9o292k&ab_channel=OllieBye

Another major event was the "Glorious Revolution" in England, so England and the Netherlands are in a personal union now. Not much to say really.

The next major conflict is the 9 years war
From 1688-1697

Some think this war was started by France to capitalize on the ongoing Great Turkish War, apparently the Sun King hadn't considered dealing with a veteran german army and veteran Anglo-Dutch fleet.
The War ended pretty terribly for everyone but the Holy Roman Empire, Ireland and Scotland now became grounds of massive unrest, violence, and civil war with the Jacobites, the Netherland's economy tanked, Spain got stomped but got the militia spirit, Piedmont was harrowed. The Empire drove the French back across the Rhine using their usual anti-French tactics, of grinding them down using Defense in Depth and forcing the French to fight bad battles and win Pyrrhic Victories
It worked, I would talk about some grand decisive battles but there aren't any.

Love France, Love non-Parisians, but every single French war post 1500 reads the same. France overextends its supply lines and fucking loses on its own terms. Hell I might even move to France one day.

Qing China and Russia have some skirmishes, which is kinda cool

Now onto the second really cool conflict

The Great Northern War (1700-1721)
For those who don't know, Sweden was once a world power, imagine Pre-WW2 Japan, but cooler.
The War really starts with the Battle of Narva where the Swedish garrison of the city wipes out half of a 37,000 man strong army despite only numbering 2000 men at the start, the Swedish relief force arrives in the middle of a snowstorm and is though to be more Russians until its too late. Its one of the coolest battles I don't have time to explain. The baltic campaign is a grinding one with the Swedes either having reinforcements encircled and destroyed by 20-40k stron Russian armies or proper Swedish armies shattering Polish, Saxon, and Russian armies alike. By 1704 the Swedes had captured all of the Baltic States and pressed as far south as Poznan in Poland

Hope yall enjoyed, sorry I couldn't go into detail.
